title: For Sale:  WALTHER PP 32 CAL. DOUBLE ACTION MILLED FINISH
postcontent: This is a fine example of German wartime small arms production.The serial  numbers puts the date at 1944. There are left slide markings which depict the Walter banner followed by Waffenfabrick Walther, Zella-Mehlis (Thur) and underneath is Walther's Patent Cal.7,65 m/m and then Mod.PP. The right slide is marked with a serial number only and the the other matching serial number is vertically below on the frame- there are no other markings on this pistol. The grips are dark brown plastic with the Walther banner at the top of each and are completely intact.. The magazine appears to be correct with the Walther banner over PP 7,65 m/m located on the left bottom edge. There are three distinct "Eagle N" military acceptance markings: one on right of cylinder, one underneath on slide and one on right forward barrel. This pistol shows little use with the bore being bright and shiny with crisp rifling. There are no import markings which may indicate it being a WW11 bring-back. Overall it is in remarkably good condition considering it's almost 70 years old!

The Polish MAG 98 9mm /9x19 NATO caliber pistol is an improved variation of the original Polish MAG95. 
It was produced for the Polish Special Forces, Border Guard and Prison Guard in the 1990's. 
Made in the Z.M. Lucznik factory 11 at Radom Poland.

In 1996 the Mag 98 was evaluated for adoption purposes by the Polish Army. It had advantages over its competition such as 
better reliability, durability and safety (better protection against accidental discharge, when dropped). 

Although the quality was deemed superior, the MAG 98 was rejected by the Army because the frame was slightly larger
than the contract qualifications called for. That was a shame because most service members prefered it and in fact

title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson DA .38 2nd model exc condition
postcontent: Here is a Smith and Wesson Double action .38 from approximately 1883. The original nickel finish comes in at about 50% with a nice even patina. The pictures look like rust but there is no rust on this pistol. According to the serial number it is a .38 double action 2nd model. These were made between 1880 and 1884 with 115000 manufactured it has a 5 digit SN which puts it around 1882 or 3. It sports what I believe is probably original S&W walnut target stocks, they are a sound tight fit and obviously have been on the gun for a long time. The gun however does not have the adjustable sights which are very rare and didnât come out until the third model. However the grips were available for the 2nd model. It is a very comfortable balanced revolver. The bore is immaculate as are the chambers with no corrosion or pitting present(how often do you see that!) The timing and lock up are right and tight and rock solid. The recoil plate shows very little signs of use as  does the front of the cylinder. I donât believe this revolver has been shot much if at all in itâs 130 years of life. The mechanics on this little guy are better than many modern revolvers.
